rrents -- tIntroduction -- tTwo Experiments in Education for Democracy -- tThe Origins of the Ecuadorian Left -- tThe Progressive Catholic Church and the Indigenous Movement in Ecuador -- tMan of Ashes -- tMen of the Rails and of the Sea -- tCreolization and African Diaspora Cultures: The Case of the Afro-Esmeraldian Décimas -- tJulio Jaramillo and Music as Identity -- tThe United Fruit Company's Legacy in Ecuador -- tThe Panama Hat Trail -- tDeforestation in Ecuador -- tCivilization and Barbarism -- tDeinstitutionalized Democracy -- tV Domination and Struggle -- tNina Pacari, an Interview -- tWomen's Movements in Twentieth-Century Ecuador -- tThe Galápagos: Environmental Pressures and Social Opportunities -- tEmerald Freedom: "With Pride in the Face of the Sun" -- tSuing ChevronTexaco -- tArts of Amazonian and Andean Women -- tVI Cultures and Identities Redefined -- tIntroduction -- tNational Identity and the First Black Miss Ecuador (1995-96) -- tEcuadorian International Migration -- tCities of Women -- tTraditional Foods of Ecuador -- tGlobalization from Below and the Political Turn among Otavalo's Merchant Artisans -- tPancho Jaime -- tBig Angel, My Love -- tNature and Humanity through Poetry -- t"Simple People" -- tThe Writings of Iván Oñate -- tSuggestions for Further Reading -- tAcknowledgment of Copyrights -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEncompassing Amazonian rainforests, Andean peaks, coastal lowlands, and the Galápagos Islands, Ecuador's geography is notably diverse. So too are its history, culture, and politics, all of which are examined from many perspectives in The Ecuador Reader. Spanning the years before the arrival of the Spanish in the early 1500s to the present, this rich anthology addresses colonialism, independence, the nation's integration into the world economy, and its tumultuous twentieth century. Interspersed among forty-eight written selections are more than three dozen images.The voices and creations of Ecuadorian politicians, writers, artists, scholars, activists, and journalists fill the Reader, from José María Velasco Ibarra, the nation's ultimate populist and five-time president, to Pancho Jaime, a political satirist; from Julio Jaramillo, a popular twentieth-century singer, to anonymous indigenous women artists who produced ceramics in the 1500s; and from the poems of Afro-Ecuadorians, to the fiction of the vanguardist Pablo Palacio, to a recipe for traditional Quiteño-style shrimp. The Reader includes an interview with Nina Pacari, the first indigenous woman elected to Ecuador's national assembly, and a reflection on how to balance tourism with the protection of the Galápagos Islands' magnificent ecosystem. Complementing selections by Ecuadorians, many never published in English, are samples of some of the best writing on Ecuador by outsiders, including an account of how an indigenous group with non-Inca origins came to see themselves as definitively Incan, an exploration of the fascination with the Andes from the 1700s to the present, chronicles of the less-than-exemplary behavior of U.S. corporations in Ecuador, an examination of Ecuadorians' overseas migration, and a look at the controversy surrounding the selection of the first black Miss Ecuador.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aClark, A. Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonilla, Adrián, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, Albert B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuerrero, Andrés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAranda, Angel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo